// ============================================================
// Detection: Windows Registry Run Key Persistence
// Technique: T1547.001 — Boot or Logon Autostart Execution: Registry Run Keys / Startup Folder
// Tactic:    Persistence (TA0003)
// Source:    Compiled from rule.yml via pySigma (microsoft_xdr pipeline), hand-reviewed
// Table:     DeviceRegistryEvents (Microsoft Defender for Endpoint / Sentinel)
// Author:    William Richardson
// Date:      2026-06-14
// ============================================================
//
// HOW THIS QUERY WORKS
// --------------------
// DeviceRegistryEvents captures registry operations from the MDE sensor.
// ActionType 'RegistryValueSet' maps to Sysmon Event ID 13.
// We look for writes to the four standard Run/RunOnce key paths (HKCU and HKLM,
// plus the 32-bit WOW6432Node equivalents) and then subtract known-good writers.
//
// FIELD REFERENCE
// ---------------
//   DeviceName            — hostname of the endpoint
//   InitiatingProcessFileName — the process that made the registry write
//   InitiatingProcessFolderPath — full path to that process's binary
//   RegistryKey           — the full registry key path being written
//   RegistryValueName     — the name of the value within the key
//   RegistryValueData     — the data written (i.e. the payload path)
//   Timestamp             — UTC time of the event
//
// FALSE POSITIVE NOTES
// --------------------
// Software installers (msiexec, per-app installers) frequently write run keys.
// The filter below excludes msiexec; tune further based on your environment.
// Do NOT add broad exclusions like "C:\Program Files\" — that path is writable
// after installation and an adversary could place a payload there.